(4, 'Other sources of financing for startups besides VCs', 'other-sources-of-financing-for-startups-besides-vcs', '<p>A healthy cash flow is essential to all businesses be it a tech startup or traditional business. While we celebrate the ramen entrepreneurs, debating about whether if it is better to bootstrap or fundraise for your startup, sometimes you just need money to make money, as the saying goes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From extra budgets in marketing so that more customers are aware of your business to hiring more staff so that the founders can delegate certain work and concentrate on the strategic aspect of the business, having more access to funding to invest into the business never hurt.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"A picture containing wall, indoor, wooden\r\n\r\nDescription automatically generated\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"height:153.5pt; margin-left:216px; margin-top:10px; width:212.75pt\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Venture capitalists are an essential part of the tech ecosystem and often provides more than just funding, but also valuable connections and know-how as well. But these are by no means a guarantee and not without trade-offs. But entrepreneurs may find themselves judged without a chance to prove themselves and so sometimes, a startup needs to be aware of the other means of accessing funds and the pros &amp; cons of each - so that they have a wide arsenal of tools in their toolbox which is always better to have and not need, than a need but not have.&nbsp;Here are 5 other channels of financing besides venture capitalists that you should be aware of and some of their pros and cons.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>#1 Crowdfunding</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Crowdfunding has gained a lot more popularity in recent years, especially after President Obama signed the Jumpstart Our Business Startups (JOBS) Act, which will allow Main Street small businesses and high-growth enterprises to raise capital from investors more efficiently. Other regions have also seen growth in the usage of crowdfunding albeit at rather different rates across regions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are 4 main types of crowdfunding - Equity, Debt, Reward and Donation. &nbsp;Donation is generally more for social and medical causes, while Reward crowdfunding is usually more suitable for B2C companies typically offering a product as a reward for a supporter&#39;s donation. The pros of reward crowdfunding are companies do not have to give up any equity and often a strong campaign result may even generate good PR, strengthening the company branding. However, there is the risk of not knowing how the campaign will turn out and with increased competition, it is no longer about just listing on a platform like Kickstarter or Indiegogo and you pray that you will get noticed with tens of thousands of listing at any one point in time. Many businesses spend thousands of dollars to prepare and make the campaign videos and much more to generate a mailing list, to ensure there will be enough eyeballs looking at the campaign when it launches. Personally, I have met campaign creators that have spent close to 6 figures on their campaigns.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Singapore, Equity crowdfunding usually starts from pre-series A companies and often have a VC leading the term sheet, setting the terms for retail investors to follow.&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.fundedhere.com/\" target=\"_blank\">FundedHere</a>&nbsp;from Singapore,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://pitchin.my/\" target=\"_blank\">PitchIN</a>&nbsp;from Malaysia are some of such crowdfunding platforms in the region.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Debt-based crowdfunding, or sometimes known as P2P lending, gained popularity in Singapore in the last decade. At last count, I tracked more than 2 dozen platforms operating at one point in time, though quite a number of them have since stopped operating or are in inactive mode. At as high as 12-20% p.a to investors and additional platform fees, there is only a narrow band of companies healthy enough to support the interest but yet not good enough to go for a bank loan that often charges not just a fraction of that, but also tend to offer a longer tenure - debt-based crowdfunding is thus suitable for a small range of companies, and probably why the local scene couldn&#39;t support the number of platforms.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With campaigns taking around 30-60 days with no guarantee they will be successfully funded, many business owners are also concerned about losing face, telling the whole world they need funding even though it does not necessarily mean the company is in trouble.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>#2 Friends, Family and Angels&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pros of raising funds from friends and family are they often become ambassadors of your business by introducing it to their circle of network.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you are going by equity instead of debt, it can be more term sheet friendly and unlike a VC which has a fund cycle, apply less pressure for early growth, allowing you to concentrate on the fundamentals such as culture, product-market fit first.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But unless you have that one rich friend, chances are you might have to raise small sums from multiple individuals. That means multiple term sheets, not to mention updates and accountability to multiple individuals, that will take your time away from running the business.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Whether or not they have strong knowledge in your domain, sometimes friends &amp; family may -just out of concern- suggest things you can do to improve the business. Of course, there are always the few know-it-alls who think they know better. I have been called stupid in my face by at least a few friends when I turned down angel investors despite them not even understanding how a term sheet works.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"A picture containing text, tree, outdoor, houseDescription automatically generated\" src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" style=\"float:left; margin-left:-6px; margin-top:20px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are also always those that come from a place of care for you, and you do have to factor in the time handling them too. Think of that nice auntie of yours who got so concerned when you got sunburnt or lost weight, except now besides thanksgiving, she has an excuse to call you every other day.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Angels, in theory, can be term sheet friendly and perhaps the best of both worlds between VCs and friends &amp; family. Traditionally, they are the been-there-done-that, rich individuals who have excelled in their industry and can bring valuable know-how to your startups. They often invest to groom the next generation of entrepreneurs, as they understand and resonate with the challenge you are going through like they did decades ago. These can be best practises from hiring to philosophy in business that cut across domains.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, with the popularity of startup investing, many retail investors have jumped onto the bandwagon and may not have a good understanding of term sheet to think win-win or understand their role as angels investors well enough to know when to support you and when to trust you as an investee.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.bansea.org/\">Bansea</a> and <a href=\"https://www.angelcentral.co/\">AngelCentral</a> are 2 of the platforms you can try to talk to if you are a seed - Pre-series A tech onwards startup from South East Asia.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>#3 Venture Debt</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Venture debt is a debt hybrid funding instrument typically available only to early- and growth-stage startups/venture-backed companies. The lenders take warrants stock to help justify the risk of them charging lower interest rates and should your startup have an exit, they walk away with an upside.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Think of it as something in-between a VC and a bank. Similar to raising from a VC, there can be complex structures and founders will do well to have a good understanding of how a cap table and term sheet work. Negotiating &amp; conducting due diligence take up tremendous time and effort and might not be worth it until you are of a certain size or stage. <a href=\"https://www.genesisventures.co/\" target=\"_blank\">Genesis Alternative Ventures</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.innovencapital.com/\" target=\"_blank\">InnoVen Capital</a>&nbsp;are some of such lenders available to startups in the region.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While generally not as dilutive as raising funding from a VC, I recommend the book, Venture Deal, whenever there is a term sheet involved, to understand terms like drag-along, call-rights to understand how different scenarios in the future affects your payout in an exit. It is one thing to own 11.4% of a $1.5 trillion company (Google&rsquo;s founders) but another to own 11.4% of a $1.5 million dollar company where there are liquidation preference terms giving an investor the first cut to take, say the first $1.45 million.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>#4 Grants</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Grants are another channel where it is invaluable for businesses to always check out before making an investment. Here in Singapore, and its pro-enterprise environment, there are many grants from various agencies to take advantage of to grow your business. From sending your people to upgrade themselves to investing in equipment, there are often something available if your need for financing is to invest in productivity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To find out more about the hundred over schemes available by the dozen of agencies, you can visit&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gobusiness.gov.sg/gov-assist/\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.gobusiness.gov.sg/gov-assist/</a>&nbsp;or book an appointment with an advisor with the many&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.enterprisesg.gov.sg/non-financial-assistance/for-singapore-companies/network-of-partners/sme-centres/overview\" target=\"_blank\">SME centres</a>&nbsp;available. If you are starting a tech startup in Singapore, you might be eligible to apply for assistance to help seed your startup -&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.startupsg.gov.sg/programmes/4894/startup-sg-founder\" target=\"_blank\">SG Startup Founder</a>.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"Justice, Scales, Balance, Lawyer, Lower\'S Fee, Money\" src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" style=\"height:153.25pt; margin-top:-47px; width:229.9pt\" /> Just like investments in roads, infrastructure, libraries, grants are meant for nation-building, are essentially taxpayers&rsquo; monies and there needs to be accountability. So that may mean lots of paperwork, reports, proposals to be filled, long waiting time between approval or claims. Be sure, to check out your eligibility, the process and the time frame to see if it is suitable or worth the effort and opportunity cost in each of your use cases.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>#5 Banks and Traditional Debt Lenders</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pure debt-based financing is arguably the easiest to understand yet probably the least discussed topic in the local startup scene. You do not have to give up your precious equity in the company and there are no complex triggers to understand. A startup is likely to just need to properly budget their cash flow to ensure they can make repayments. That said, a startup ought to still enquire with as many lenders as possible to ensure they have the most suitable deal, such as a long tenure, low-interest rate or as large a quantum as possible, whichever matters most to you.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Many businesses are unaware that besides banks, there is a whole host of other legal entities that can provide business &amp; personal financing and loans, such as finance companies, licensed moneylenders, excluded moneylenders, and fintech lenders. Their legislative differences vary from country to country, but generally, 1 of the things that differentiate them is where their source of funds comes from to facilitate lending. For example, banks can accept deposits from consumers while fintech companies generally raise their funds from private or institutional investors.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Plenty of reputable fintech lending companies in Singapore actually hold moneylender licenses in order to lend to business owners that are sole proprietors and partners as they are not considered a corporation for an excluded moneylender to lend to without a need for a license Many crowdfunding companies also at times lend to selected borrowers using their own funds, instead of listing it as a campaign.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sometimes startups consider only VCs and angels as assume that they are too young to qualify for banks and traditional lenders. However, many of our Financing Partners are able to lend to companies as young as just a few months old. Going for products like Invoice Financing, Merchant cash advance also allows lenders to focus less on your short track record but on your customer and future receivables instead. Else pledging your assets to get a secured loan which tends to be cheaper in interest rate, is another way to get the financing you need to fund your business.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But with more than dozens of lenders just for SMEs in Singapore, it can be quite a chore to contact them one by one, and not comparing around may mean paying thousands of dollars extra in interests and fees. The federal reserve estimates the average SME in the US takes around 4 full man-days of work hours to find a loan.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"FindTheLoan.com\">FindTheLoan.com</a> is a fully digitalized end-to-end loan comparison platform where you can now reach dozens of banks and lenders directly in minutes with just one submission, not days, and get actual quotes based on your credit profile, not best-case scenarios, not some advertised rates. You also no longer need to liaise with relationship managers from different financial institutes, calling you during meetings or lunchtimes, allowing you to concentrate on your business.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What sort of financing have you sought before or intend to seek next? Share with us more and why below! Do to share with us your industry too so we can better understand where you are coming from.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'blog20211110-024221.jpg', 1, '2021-09-08 12:13:59', '2021-11-10 02:44:11');

(5, 'Common mistakes made when refinancing property loan', 'common-mistakes-made-when-refinancing-property-loan', '<p><img alt=\"Home, House, Interior, Design, Living, Bedroom, Side\" src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" style=\"height:416px; width:624px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>A recent survey shows many homeowners are not even aware they can refinance their property. For those who know, there are often a few major mistakes made:</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Not comparing around</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A property is often a person&rsquo;s largest investment in life, and so a home loan is usually the biggest loan we will ever take. Often spanning a few decades and costing hundreds of thousands, many homeowners take more time to find the perfect colour to paint their wall than to find a suitable loan. Instead, they will just take the time to enquire from the few banks they are familiar with or recommended by other homeowners - when rates are constantly changing-even though what may be applicable to them might not be applicable to you because of different borrower&rsquo;s profiles.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A loan of just $500,000 and spanning 30 years at 1.35% and 1.45% p.a have a difference of $15,000 in interest.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Not comparing all other factors</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another mistake made by property owners is jumping at the new and lower interest rate they found, failing to take the terms and conditions of both their existing and new loans into consideration.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A bank may offer a competitive rate, but lock you in for a period of time. This may work for you if you believe the interest rate will trend higher and you will not be refinancing your loan any time soon. However, if that is not the case, without taking into consideration of the early redemption fee, it may erode any savings you may enjoy when refinancing into a lower interest rate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At times, a banker or broker may be excited to share with you how much lower you might be paying each month, but forgetting to mention that there are other fees such as valuation and legal fees that may be incurred again. Make sure you also compare these fees, instead of just comparing the monthly instalment you have to pay.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"A picture containing indoor, apple, fruit, red\r\n\r\nDescription automatically generated\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"float:left; height:327px; width:218px\" /><strong>Not comparing apple to apple</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A new loan with the same interest rate calculated with a 30 years repayment vs a 15 years repayment will naturally show a much lower monthly installment, as you are spreading it out over a longer period, although your overall interest paid is much higher.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Make sure that when you are comparing a quote, the new loan&#39;s tenure is equal to your current remainder (e.g 20 years loan with 10 years left) to ensure there are real savings and not because of how it is presented.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Also, it is important to understand how amortization works. In amortization, the monthly repayment of the first few years largely goes towards paying off the interest and not the principal. You cannot assume that if you have been paying the loan for half of its tenure, the outstanding principal is halved. So, ensure the math is done on the correct outstanding to have an accurate quote.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'blog20211110-024655.jpg', 1, '2021-11-10 02:46:55', '2021-11-10 02:46:55');

-- Table structure for table `loan_quotations`
--

CREATE TABLE `loan_quotations` (
  `id` bigint(20) UNSIGNED NOT NULL,
  `apply_loan_id` int(11) DEFAULT NULL,
  `partner_id` int(11) DEFAULT NULL,
  `quoted_by` int(11) DEFAULT NULL COMMENT 'user_id of financePartner user who put this quotation',
  `quantum_interest` text COLLATE utf8mb4_unicode_ci NOT NULL,
  `one_time_fee` text COLLATE utf8mb4_unicode_ci NOT NULL,
  `monthly_fee` text COLLATE utf8mb4_unicode_ci NOT NULL,
  `annual_fee` text COLLATE utf8mb4_unicode_ci NOT NULL,
  `legal_fee` text COLLATE utf8mb4_unicode_ci DEFAULT NULL,
  `if_insurance_required` text COLLATE utf8mb4_unicode_ci NOT NULL,
  `eir` text COLLATE utf8mb4_unicode_ci DEFAULT NULL,
  `repayment` text COLLATE utf8mb4_unicode_ci DEFAULT NULL COMMENT 'contains info about repayment terms, remarks(Seen by all internal users), Personal notepad (read only by me)',
  `status` tinyint(4) DEFAULT NULL,
  `quote_validity` date DEFAULT NULL,
  `created_at` timestamp NULL DEFAULT NULL,
  `updated_at` timestamp NULL DEFAULT NULL,
  `proceeded_at` datetime DEFAULT NULL,
  `offer_signed_at` datetime DEFAULT NULL,
  `offer_disbursed_at` datetime DEFAULT NULL
) ENGINE=InnoDB DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8mb4 COLLATE=utf8mb4_unicode_ci;

(9, 'glossary', '<p>Large customers tend to ask for longer credit terms such as 90, 120 days which may affect your cashflow. Suppliers or service providers often have little choice for fear of losing the customers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To unlike these cashflows, you may look to our Financing Partners for invoice financing on FindTheLoan.com. Alternatively, Dynamic Discounting or Early Payment Discount may be something you can offer to your clients in order to give them an incentive to pay up earlier. By offering a discount for early settlement on invoices, your company has more cash flow to invest in innovation and inventories, hiring and training, all while preserving the relationship with your customers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The difference between Dynamic Discounting and early payment, is instead of just fixed terms like for example a simple 2% discount within 60 days - it allows the supplier to &quot;dynamically&quot; adjust the rate on a decreasing percent per day or per set number of days, for example, every 7 days. Besides, giving the customer more flexibility, it also encourages the customer to settle the invoice much earlier than the 60 days used in Early Payment Discount.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"height:341px; width:595px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>An importer with surplus cash getting a 2% discount on paying up in 30 days instead of 60 days on ten million dollars&rsquo; worth of invoices each year has not just a $200,000 improvement on the bottom line but is probably much more than any interest he or she can earn from leaving that cash in the account.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Or if your customer can obtain Purchase Order financing on FindTheLoan.com at a lower rate than the discount, they can even arbitrage the difference.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2021-11-03 07:49:16', '2021-11-03 08:00:50');
